1.1 - ETL¶

We begin by loading the data.

In [3]:
import re

file = open('auto-mpg.data.txt', "r")
lines = file.readlines()

mpg = []
cylinders = []
displacement = []
horsepower = []
weight = []
acceleration = []
model_year = []
origin = []
car_name = []

columns = [mpg, cylinders, displacement, horsepower, weight, acceleration, model_year, origin, car_name]

for line in lines:
    #next 3 lines format the name of the car
    line = line.replace('\t','    ')
    line = line.replace('\n','') 
    line = line.replace('"','') 
    dataValues = re.split('\s{2,}', line) # all values have at least 2 spaces between them (car names have 1 space in the name)
    for index, val in enumerate(dataValues):
        columns[index].append(val)

From reading the "names" file, we see the nine attributes of mpg, cylinders, displacement, horsepower, weight, acceleration, model year, origin, and the name of the car. We can use this information to parse the lines of the real data in the other .txt file.

There are 398 values for all variables, however, all of our data was loaded as strings - we'll need to convert to number types to be useful. In addition, we happen to conveniently know from our provided description that 6 values of "horsepower" are missing and replaced with '?'. What we choose to do is see if one of the other variables will be a good predictor for horsepower.

In [6]:
tempCars = cars[cars.horsepower != '?']
tempCars = tempCars.reset_index()
for col in tempCars.columns[:-1]:
    tempCars.loc[:,col] = pd.to_numeric(tempCars[col])

We have converted a copy of our data to numerical quantities so that we may find the highest correlated variable:

In [7]:
correlations = {}
for var in tempCars.columns[:-2]:
    correlationValue = stats.pearsonr(tempCars.horsepower, tempCars[var])[0]
    correlations[correlationValue] = var
        
highestCorrelationValue = sorted(correlations.keys())[-2] #second highest because horsepower is most correlated with itself
print(correlations[highestCorrelationValue], ":", highestCorrelationValue)

displacement : 0.8972570018434688

We see that displacement is highly correlated with horsepower, and so we shall just use this variable to build a quick model for the missing horsepower values.

In [8]:
import models
In [9]:
hp_model = 'horsepower ~ displacement'
hp_result = models.bootstrap_linear_regression(hp_model, data=tempCars)
models.describe_bootstrap_lr(hp_result)
Out[9]:
Linear Regression Results
Coefficients
$\theta$95% BCI
($\beta_0$)40.31(37.37, 43.57)
displacement ($\beta_1$)0.33(0.31, 0.34)
Metrics
$\sigma$17.02(15.45, 18.29)
$R^2$0.81(0.77, 0.84)

With an $R^2$ of 0.81, we decide that this model is good enough to use to account for our missing values of horsepower, rather than getting rid of those 6 rows of data.

In [10]:
beta0 = hp_result['coefficients'][0]
beta1 = hp_result['coefficients'][1]

for i in range(len(cars)):
    if cars.iloc[i].horsepower == '?':
        cars.iloc[i].horsepower = beta0 + beta1*float(cars.iloc[i][correlations[highestCorrelationValue]])

We have finally accounted for our missing horsepower values, and can now cast the rest of the data to numerical types.

def histogram(data,column,bins=50,weights=None):
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    
    axes.set_xlabel(column)
    axes.set_ylabel("Count")
    
    axes.hist(data[column], bins=bins, color=mainColor,ec='black',weights=weights)
    axes.set_title("Count Histogram of " + column + "; " + str(bins) + " bins")
    axes.grid(zorder=0)
    
    plt.show()
    plt.close()
In [17]:
from matplotlib.ticker import PercentFormatter as PF

def bars(data,column,rotation=0,normalize=False,defaultSort=True):
    counts = data[column].value_counts().sort_index()
    if defaultSort:
        proportions = data[column].value_counts(normalize=normalize).sort_index()*((100*normalize)+1-normalize)
    else:    
        proportions = data[column].value_counts(normalize=normalize)*((100*normalize)+1-normalize)
        
    x = range(len(counts))
    width = 1/1.5
    
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    
    axes.bar(x, proportions, width, color=mainColor, align="center", ec='black')
    axes.set_xlabel(column)
    axes.set_xticks(x)
    axes.set_xticklabels(proportions.axes[0])

    if normalize:
        axes.set_ylabel("Percent")
        axes.yaxis.set_major_formatter(PF())
    else:
        axes.set_ylabel("Count")

        #     axes.xaxis.grid(False)
    plt.setp(axes.xaxis.get_majorticklabels(), rotation=rotation)        
    axes.set_title("Relative Frequency of "+column)
        
    plt.show()
    plt.close()
In [18]:
from matplotlib.ticker import PercentFormatter as PF

def hbars(data,column,rotation=0,normalize=False,defaultSort=True):
    counts = data[column].value_counts().sort_index()
    if defaultSort:
        proportions = data[column].value_counts(normalize=normalize).sort_index()*((100*normalize)+1-normalize)
    else:    
        proportions = data[column].value_counts(normalize=normalize)*((100*normalize)+1-normalize)
        
    y = list(range(len(counts)))
    width = 1/1.5
    
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    
    axes.barh(y, proportions, width, color=mainColor, align="center", ec='black')
    axes.set_ylabel(column)
    axes.set_yticks(y)
    axes.set_yticklabels(proportions.axes[0])

    if normalize:
        axes.set_xlabel("Percent")
        axes.xaxis.set_major_formatter(PF())
    else:
        axes.set_xlabel("Count")

    plt.setp(axes.xaxis.get_majorticklabels(), rotation=rotation)        
    axes.set_title("Relative Frequency of "+column)
        
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

Cylinders¶

The cylinders of an engine is usually a proxy for essentially how big the engine is. Typical counts for the cylinders are 4, 6, or 8. We also know that these values are discrete and typically don't get higher than 16 (https://www.motor1.com/features/239145/most-powerful-engines-cylinders/#:~:text=16%20Cylinders%20%2D%20Bugatti%208.0%2DLiter,more%20cylinders%20than%20any%20other) and so we can treat this variable as discrete.

def describeCategory(df, num, cat, trans=False):
    grouped = df.groupby(cat)
    groupedY = grouped[num].describe()

        print(groupedY.transpose())

In [50]:
def reorder(order, unsorted):
    zipped_lists = zip(order, unsorted)
    sorted_zipped_lists = sorted(zipped_lists)
    sorted_list = [element for _, element in sorted_zipped_lists]
    return sorted_list

# code adapted from course notes

import eda as eda
def multiboxplot(data, numeric, categorical, width=10, skip_data_points=True, prefix='', vert=True, defaultSort=True):

    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(width, 6))
    
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    
    grouped = data.groupby(categorical)
    labels = pd.unique(data[categorical].values)
    try:
        labels.sort()
    except:
        cat=True
        
    grouped_data = [grouped[numeric].get_group( k) for k in labels]
    if defaultSort:
        patch = axes.boxplot(grouped_data, labels=labels, patch_artist=True, zorder=1, vert=vert)
    else:
        
        mappings = [(x.median(),index) for index,x in enumerate(grouped_data)]
        map2 = list(range(len(mappings)))
        mappings.sort()
        indices = [x[1] for x in mappings]
        order = reorder(indices,map2)
        sorted_grouped_data = reorder(order,grouped_data)
        sorted_labels = reorder(order,labels)
        patch = axes.boxplot(sorted_grouped_data, labels=sorted_labels, patch_artist=True, zorder=1, vert=vert)

    eda.restyle_boxplot(patch)
    
    if not skip_data_points:
        for i, k in enumerate(labels):
            subdata = grouped[numeric].get_group( k)
            x = np.random.normal(i + 1, 0.01, size=len(subdata))
            axes.plot(x, subdata, 'o', alpha=0.4, color=mainColor, zorder=2)
    
    if vert==True:
        axes.set_xlabel(categorical)
        axes.set_ylabel(numeric)
    else:
        axes.set_ylabel(categorical)
        axes.set_xlabel(numeric)
    axes.set_title("{0}Distribution of {1} by {2}".format(prefix, numeric, categorical))
    
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

# code adapted from course notes

def scatterJX(df,x,y,jitter=0,alpha=1):
    '''Scatter plot with jitter added on X Axis'''
    
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)

    originalX = df[x]
    np.random.seed(0)
    jitterX = originalX + stats.norm.rvs(0, jitter, originalX.size)

    axes.scatter(jitterX, df[y], marker="o", color=mainColor, alpha=alpha)

    if jitter!=0:
        suffix = ", (jitter added)"
    else:
        suffix = ""
    axes.set_title(y + " vs " + x + suffix)
    
    axes.set_xlabel(x) 
    axes.set_ylabel(y)
    
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

def createModel(features, df):
    model = 'mpg ~ ' + ' + '.join(features)
    result = models.bootstrap_linear_regression(model, data=df)
    
    return result

# code adapted from course notes

def plotResiduals(result,features,df,labels=False):

    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))

    plots = len(features)
    rows = (plots // 2) + 1

    for index, feature in enumerate(features):
        axes = figure.add_subplot(rows, 2, index + 1)

        keyed_values = sorted(zip(df[feature].values, result["residuals"]), key=lambda x: x[0])
        residuals = [x[1][0] for x in keyed_values]
        
        if labels==True:
            axes.plot([x[0] for x in keyed_values], residuals, '.', color=mainColor, alpha=0.85)
        else:
            axes.plot(list(range(0, result["n"])), residuals, '.', color=mainColor, alpha=0.85)

        axes.axhline(y=0.0, xmin=0, xmax=result["n"], c="firebrick", alpha=0.6)
        axes.set_title(feature + " v. residuals")

    figure.tight_layout(pad=3.0)
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

def color_negative_red(val):
    """
    Takes a scalar and returns a string with
    the css property `'color: red'` for negative
    strings, black otherwise.
    """
    color = 'red' if abs(val) > 0.8 else 'black'

In [75]:
def correlationMatrix(features):
    '''
        Display the correlations between each feature in our model and return high correlations in red
    '''    
    cols = []

    for col in features:
        rows = []
        for row in features:
            rows.append(stats.pearsonr(cars[row], cars[col])[0])
        cols.append(rows)

    df = pd.DataFrame(cols, columns = features, index=features)
    df = df.style.applymap(color_negative_red)
    
    return df

We now begin to build a linear model to estimate mpg. There are a few numerical variables that we may want to treat as categorical later, (namely cylinders and model_year), but for now we shall only create one hot encodings for the "origin" variable. # code adapted from course notes

def data_collection():
    result = dict()
    result[ "train"] = defaultdict( list)
    result[ "test"] = defaultdict( list)
    return result
In [86]:
# code adapted from course notes

def chunk(xs, n):
    k, m = divmod(len(xs), n)
    return [xs[i * k + min(i, m):(i + 1) * k + min(i + 1, m)] for i in range(n)]
In [87]:
# code adapted from course notes

def validation_curves(algorithm, formulas, data, values, evaluate, fold_count=10, repetitions=3, increment=1):
    indices = list(range(len( data)))
    results = data_collection()
    for _ in range(repetitions):
        random.shuffle(indices)
        folds = chunk(indices, fold_count)
        for fold in folds:
            test_data = data.iloc[ fold]
            train_indices = [idx for idx in indices if idx not in fold]
            train_data = data.iloc[train_indices]
            for i, p in enumerate(zip(formulas, values)):
                f, v = p
                # it's ok to resuse the folds for each v of values
                # we calculate the model
                result = algorithm(f, train_data, v)
                model = result["model"]
                # we calculate the results for the training data subset
                y, X = patsy.dmatrices(f, train_data, return_type="matrix")
                result = models.summarize(f, X, y, model)
                metric = evaluate(result)
                results["train"][i].append( metric)
                
                # we calculate the results for the test data.
                y, X = patsy.dmatrices(f, test_data, return_type="matrix")
                result = models.summarize(f, X, y, model)
                metric = evaluate(result)
                results["test"][i].append( metric)
            #
        #
    # process results
    # Rely on the CLT...
    statistics = {}
    for k, v in results["train"].items():
        statistics[ k] = (np.mean(v), np.std(v))
    results["train"] = statistics
    statistics = {}
    for k, v in results["test"].items():
        statistics[ k] = (np.mean(v), np.std(v))
    results["test"] = statistics
    return results

# code adapted from course notes

def results_to_curves( curve, results):
    all_statistics = results[ curve]
    keys = list( all_statistics.keys())
    keys.sort()
    mean = []
    upper = []
    lower = []
    for k in keys:
        m, s = all_statistics[ k]
        mean.append( m)
        upper.append( m + 2 * s)
        lower.append( m - 2 * s)
    return keys, lower, mean, upper
In [89]:
# code adapted from course notes

def plot_validation_curves( results, metric, parameter, values, zoom=False):
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)

    xs, train_lower, train_mean, train_upper = results_to_curves( "train", results)
    _, test_lower, test_mean, test_upper = results_to_curves( "test", results)

    axes.plot( values, train_mean, color="steelblue")
    axes.fill_between( values, train_upper, train_lower, color="steelblue", alpha=0.25, label="train")
    axes.plot( values, test_mean, color="firebrick")
    axes.fill_between( values, test_upper, test_lower, color="firebrick", alpha=0.25, label="test")
    axes.legend()
    axes.set_xlabel( parameter)
    axes.set_ylabel( metric)
    axes.set_title("Validation Curves")

    if zoom:
        y_lower = int( 0.9 * np.amin([train_lower[-1], test_lower[-1]]))
        y_upper = int( 1.1 * np.amax([train_upper[-1], test_upper[-1]]))
        axes.set_ylim((y_lower, y_upper))

    plt.show()
    plt.close()

Notice that we first created a new feature, "years_after_1969". It makes sense to scale the model_year in this way if we are to apply a polynomial to it. This way, differences in year can be more precisely measured.

# code adapted from course notes

def mean_scale(df, variable):
    x_bar = df[ variable].mean()
    std = df[ variable].std()
    scaled_variable = (df[ variable] - x_bar) / (2.0 * std) # suggested by Gelman
    df[ variable + "_scaled"] = scaled_variable

1.4 - Describe the model¶

Description of Coefficients¶

Let's take a minute now to describe our final model that we have created.

In [131]:
print(final_model)

mpg ~ recip_weight_scaled + acceleration + post_1969_raised_2_1 + Japan + modern + modern:Europe + modern:Japan + cylinders_3 + cylinders_5 + cylinders_6 + cylinders_8

We see that our model has 11 features. Let's describe these, but first let's start with the intercept, $\beta_0$.

Our intercept represents cars that have 4 cylinders, are not Japanese, (recall that we dropped our "Europe" feature making the one hot encoding for country origin into a binary), and not 'modern', (meaning it was made before 1978). These cars on average will have an mpg rating of about 20.24, before considering other factors. We are 95% sure that this value would truly be somewhere in the range of 17.94 and 22.48.

Our next feature is the mean scaled reciprocal of the weight of the car. We see a coefficient of 9.68 and we are quite sure that this value is positive. Taking the reciprocal of the weight means that we now expect a positive coefficient as an increase in this value would actually correspond to a decreased weight. We have also scaled this feature, meaning that every unit increase above the average would result in an extra 9.68 mpg.

Acceleration has a slight positive effect on mpg which is what we predicted after our EDA, but note that 0 falls within the 95% BCI and so this feature is weaker relative to most of our other included features.

The next feature is a little difficult to interpret as well, but we are taking the number of years after 1969 that a car was made, and raising this value to a polynomial of 2.1. A one unit increase here will result in a slight increase (0.03) in our mpg. This makes sense as our prediction is that cars overall become more fuel efficient as time progresses. ALso note that while this effect is weak, we also do not see 0 in our 95% BCI so we are fairly certain it does indeed have a positive effect on mpg.

The next two features are both encoding variables representing whether a car was made in Japan or was made after 1978. We expected both of these features to have a positive effect and they do have positive coefficients, yet note that both of these also contain 0 in their 95% BCI meaning they have relatively weak explanatory value.

The next two variables are interaction variables between "modern" and either Europe or Japan. Both of these features have positive effects on mpg, and 0 is not included in either 95% BCI meaning we can be fairly certain that if a car is both "modern" and from either Europe or Japan then it should have better fuel efficiency relative to our "intercept".

Finally, we have our one hot encoding variables for the number of cylinders in a car, and we chose to leave 4 cylinder cars in the intercept so that we could obtain more accurate base values. Note that 3 and 5 cylinder cars both have very small sample size and so these observations are not very trustworthy. We choose to leave them included so that we can claim that our intercept is a 4 cylinder car. We see negative coefficient values for 6 and 8 cylinder cars meaning that as the number of cylinders of a car increases, the car's fuel efficiency should decrease. 0 is not included in these 95% BCI's, and so we are fairly confident in these effects.

Cross Validation¶

Let's evaluate our final model with 3 rounds of 10 fold cross validation.

In [134]:
# code adapted from course notes

def sse(results):
    errors = results['residuals']
    n = len( errors)
    squared_error = np.sum( [e**2 for e in errors])
    return np.sqrt((1.0/n) * squared_error)
In [135]:
# code adapted from course notes

def cross_validation(algorithm, formula, data, evaluate=sse, fold_count=10, repetitions=3):
    indices = list(range(len( data)))
    metrics_sse = []
    metrics_r_squared = []
    for _ in range(repetitions):
        random.shuffle(indices)
        folds = chunk(indices, fold_count)
        for fold in folds:
            test_data = data.iloc[fold]
            train_indices = [idx not in fold for idx in indices]
            train_data = data.iloc[train_indices]
            result = algorithm(formula, data=train_data)
            model = result["model"]
            y, X = patsy.dmatrices(formula, test_data, return_type="matrix")
            # y = np.ravel( y) # might need for logistic regression
            results = models.summarize(formula, X, y, model)
            metric_sse = sse(results)
            metric_r_squared = results["r_squared"]
            
            metrics_sse.append(metric_sse)
            metrics_r_squared.append(metric_r_squared)
    return metrics_sse, metrics_r_squared

# code adapted from course notes

def resample(data):
    n = len(data)
    return [data[ i] for i in [stats.randint.rvs(0, n - 1) for _ in range( 0, n)]]

Learning Curves¶

Let's see if more data would help our model by building some learning curves.

In [143]:
# code adapted from course notes

def learning_curves(algorithm, formula, data, evaluate, fold_count=10, repetitions=3,increment=1):
    indices = list(range(len( data)))
    results = data_collection()
    for _ in range(repetitions):
        random.shuffle(indices)
        folds = chunk(indices, fold_count)
        for fold in folds:
            test_data = data.iloc[ fold]
            train_indices = [idx for idx in indices if idx not in fold]
            train_data = data.iloc[train_indices]
            for i in list(range(increment, 100, increment)) + [100]: # ensures 100% is always picked.
            # the indices are already shuffled so we only need to take ever increasing chunks
                train_chunk_size = int( np.ceil((i/100)*len( train_indices)))
                train_data_chunk = data.iloc[train_indices[0:train_chunk_size]]
                # we calculate the model
                result = algorithm(formula, data=train_data_chunk)
                model = result["model"]
                # we calculate the results for the training data subset
                y, X = patsy.dmatrices( formula, train_data_chunk, return_type="matrix")
                result = models.summarize(formula, X, y, model)
                metric = evaluate(result)
                results["train"][i].append( metric)
                # we calculate the results for the test data.
                y, X = patsy.dmatrices( formula, test_data, return_type="matrix")
                result = models.summarize(formula, X, y, model)
                metric = evaluate(result)
                results["test"][i].append( metric)
    #
    #
    # process results
    # Rely on the CLT...
    statistics = {}
    for k, v in results["train"].items():
        statistics[ k] = (np.mean(v), np.std(v))
    results["train"] = statistics
    statistics = {}
    for k, v in results["test"].items():
        statistics[ k] = (np.mean(v), np.std(v))
    results["test"] = statistics
    return results

# code adapted from course notes

def plot_learning_curves( results, metric, desired=None, zoom=False, credible=True):
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    xs, train_lower, train_mean, train_upper = results_to_curves( "train", results)
    _, test_lower, test_mean, test_upper = results_to_curves( "test", results)
    axes.plot( xs, train_mean, color="steelblue", label="train")
    axes.plot( xs, test_mean, color="firebrick", label="test")
    
    if credible:
        axes.fill_between( xs, train_upper, train_lower, color="steelblue", alpha=0.25)
        axes.fill_between( xs, test_upper, test_lower, color="firebrick", alpha=0.25)
    if desired:
        if type(desired) is tuple:
            axes.axhline((desired[0] + desired[1])/2.0, color="gold", label="desired")
            axes.fill_between( xs, desired[1], desired[0], color="gold", alpha=0.25)
        else:
            axes.axhline( desired, color="gold", label="desired")
        
    axes.legend()
    axes.set_xlabel( "training set (%)")
    axes.set_ylabel( metric)
    axes.set_title("Learning Curves")
    if zoom:
        y_lower = int( 0.9 * np.amin([train_lower[-1], test_lower[-1]]))
        y_upper = int( 1.1 * np.amax([train_upper[-1], test_upper[-1]]))
        axes.set_ylim((y_lower, y_upper))
    plt.show()
    plt.close()
In [145]:
curveResults = learning_curves(models.linear_regression, final_model, cars, sse, increment=5)
In [146]:
plot_learning_curves(curveResults, r"SSE", desired=(2.5, 3), credible=False)

Between about 20-40% of our training set size we see our train and test curves begin to converge. This indicates that we are in a relatively high bias scenario and if we wanted to further improve our final model, gathering more data would be unlikely to help.

So our first entry happens to be less than one standard deviation away from the true value. If all of our values were normally distributed, we would expect the errors to be with one standard deviation 68% of the time and within two 95% of the time. What is our 95% bounds on our estimate?

In [151]:

(10.21, 20.79)

95% of the time we would expect a car with attributes like our first car to have an mpg between 10.21 and 20.79. What if we had no information about these features at all?

In [152]:
mean_mpg = cars.mpg.mean()
std_mpg = cars.mpg.std()
print("({0:.2f}, {1:.2f})".format(mean_mpg - 2 * std_mpg, mean_mpg + 2* std_mpg))

(7.88, 39.15)

We saw earlier that mpg was not quite normally distributed, so the above bounds are not quite 95% intervals. By looking at 2 standard deviations from the mean, Chebyshev's inequality tells us that we can be guaranteed that just 75% of the values for mpg will fall within a range of 7.88 and 39.15. Even if we could claim that mpg were normally distributed, this 95% bound would still be far larger than what we obtain using our final model. Let's now check to see if indeed are our errors are normally distributed.

In [153]:
errors = []
for index in range(len(cars)):
    features_array = [1]
    for feature in final_features:
        features_array.append(cars[feature].iloc[index])
    predicted_MPG = final_result["model"].predict(np.array([features_array]))[0][0]
    actual_MPG = cars.mpg[index]
    errors.append(predicted_MPG - actual_MPG)

Above we have calculated the errors between the prediction our model gives and the actual value. Below we visualize these results.
